# Code Quality Standards

## Verification (ALWAYS do these)

Before claiming any work is complete:
1. **Run tests** - Execute the test suite and report results
2. **Check lint errors** - Run linter and fix any issues
3. **Verify build** - Ensure the project builds/compiles successfully
4. **Confirm functionality** - Describe what was tested and how

Never say "Done!" without evidence that changes work.

## Comments

### DO
- Add WHY comments for non-obvious logic
- Document breaking changes
- Explain trade-offs and constraints
- Note workarounds and their reasons

### DON'T
- Add obvious comments ("// Import the module", "// Loop through array")
- Leave commented-out code
- Explain what code does (code should be self-documenting)
- Add TODO comments without context

## Structure

### File Organization
- Keep imports at the top of the file
- No inline imports (importing inside functions)
- Group related imports together
- Order: stdlib → third-party → local

### Code Changes
- Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- Make small, incremental changes
- Each function should do one thing well
- Keep files focused - split if >500 lines

## Error Handling

### DO
- Handle all error cases explicitly
- Provide meaningful error messages with context
- Log errors with relevant data for debugging
- Prefer graceful degradation over crashing

### DON'T
- Swallow exceptions silently (`except: pass`)
- Use generic error messages ("An error occurred")
- Let errors propagate without logging
- Assume external calls will succeed

## Documentation

### When to Update
- API/interface changes → Update docs immediately
- Breaking changes → Document in changelog
- New features → Add to README if user-facing
- Configuration changes → Update relevant docs

### Function Signatures
- Clear parameter names
- Type annotations where applicable
- Docstring for non-obvious functions
- Document exceptions that may be raised

## Quality Checklist

Before completing any task, verify:

- [ ] Tests pass (or explain why not testable)
- [ ] No lint errors
- [ ] Build succeeds
- [ ] No obvious comments added
- [ ] WHY comments for complex logic
- [ ] Error cases handled
- [ ] Documentation updated if needed
